    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>St. Hilda's Episcopal Church in River Rouge can date its history back to 1897 when several interested families in the area held a meeting in their home. The result was St. Mark's Mission under the care of the Rev. George N. Harris, rector of St. Stephen's, Wyandotte. In 1906 the mission was renamed the Mission of the Advent.</p>
      <p>After the mission was well established, the members purchased land on the corner of Genesee and Batavia, where in 1910-1911 the first frame church building was erected. The name St. Hilda's was suggested by a member after his mother church in Hartlepool, England. On November 13, 1921, Dean Warren L. Rogers of St. Paul's Cathedral laid the cornerstone for the new church building, but the new church was not to be. Only the basement section was completed.</p>
      <p>In December 1943, the mission became free of debt. Papers of incorporation as a parish were taken out in November 1943 and St. Hilda's was accepted as a parish at the 111th Annual Convention of the Diocese of Michigan in January 1944.</p>
      <p>After World War II, the church raised funds on its own without the aid of the Diocese. By April 1953 there were sufficient funds to erect a church building. At this time the old frame building was torn down, and construction of the new brick church began.</p>
      <p>Due to declining membership in the 1990s and the first decade of the new century, St. Hilda's ceased operation in 2011.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The records of St. Hilda's have been arranged into the following series: Registers of baptisms, communicants, burials, marriages, etc.; Register of church services; Church governance; Women's Organizations; Membership records; Weekly Bulletins and Programs of Special Events; and Office files.</p>
    </scopecontent>
